00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:28.910
So basically, you can read a
lot about dual-track agile.

00:04:28.910 --> 00:04:32.890
I highly recommend an
article from, more or less,

00:04:32.890 --> 00:04:36.920
10 years ago from Marty Cagan
from the Silicon Valley Product

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:39.350
Group that explains a lot
about the methodology.

00:04:39.350 --> 00:04:43.340
But the basic concept is you
have basically two tracks.

00:04:43.340 --> 00:04:45.800
In discovery, you try to
figure out what to build.

00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:49.910
In delivery, you deliver
what you already validated.

00:04:49.910 --> 00:04:53.210
And so having our process,
our development process,

00:04:53.210 --> 00:04:55.070
considering these two
different moments,

00:04:55.070 --> 00:04:58.520
they are both tentative
moments, was key for us

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.500
because, in discovery,
we use techniques

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:04.640
like design springs,
prototyping, research

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:08.240
to quickly validate hypotheses,
to formulate and validate

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:09.980
hypotheses.

